Rhodi: this city was, until the time of Claudius, nominally inde— pendent of Rome. Tiberius was therefore, during his residence at Rhodes, legally outside of the bounds of the empire.

iis . . . annis: B.C. 6 to A.D. 2; this was in appearance a voluntary retirement, but as he was not per- mitted by Augustus to return,-he was to all intents and purposes an exile; remansit ergo Rhodi contra voluntatem (Suet. Tib. 12). The cause of this retirem'ent is not cer- tain. Tacitus, chap. 53, attributes it to the infidelities of his wife Julia, daughter of Augustus.
